Passeport bundles the following third-party software in
Passeport.app/Contents/Helpers. All are permissively licensed; Passeport ships
no GPL-licensed binaries and no GNU tooling. The full upstream license texts are
reproduced under Passeport.app/Contents/Resources/licenses/ (copied from each
crate at bundle time); this file is a summary index.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
rage, rage-keygen — https://github.com/str4d/rage
    Copyright (c) The rage Developers
    Licensed under either of Apache License 2.0 or MIT license, at your option.
    (age encryption; pure-Rust RustCrypto backend, no native crypto libraries.)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
passeport-core — this project
    Copyright (c) Passeport authors
    Licensed under the MIT license.
    (Key derivation, the scdaemon dialect, the age plugin, the self-contained
    `minisign` CLI (sign + verify), and the self-contained pure-Rust `gpg`
    drop-in for Mode 2. No third-party gpg / minisign / rsign2 is bundled —
    these are all implemented here.)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Explicitly NOT bundled: sequoia-chameleon-gnupg. It is GPL-3.0-or-later, links
native (L)GPL crypto (Nettle/GMP or OpenSSL), and requires an external GnuPG
gpg-agent — so it cannot be part of a permissive, self-contained, GNU-free
distribution. Passeport's OpenPGP support is provided instead by the pure-Rust
`passeport-core gpg` drop-in (Mode 2), which delegates the private-key operation
to the app over the Touch ID-gated bridge.
